column5: Clustered Controlled Trial DISCO;DISCO-SET;"The general practitioner is confronted with unselected smokers whose attempts to quit smoking are often repeated over time before leading to a definitive cessation.

column2: 3-5% of smokers succeed in quitting in the general population. The corollary is that the majority of smokers are in a situation of failure in their attempt to quit: 33% declared during the 2019 French Health Barometer to have made an attempt of at least 7 days in the past year. Thus
column3: this status of ""smoker"" can cover a wide variety of situations: no attempt to stop smoking
column4: attempt(s) of more or less clinical significance
column5: previous support or not by a health professional
column7: the HAS recommendations do not determine a specific course of action for these smokers
column8: whose experiences may be very different. It could therefore be interesting to objectivize the smoking cessation process of these patients who have or have not succeeded in quitting
column9: in order to deduce profiles of smokers according to their previous smoking cessation experiences. Furthermore
column10: the choice and relevance of the cessation criteria used are debated.

column1: Following the randomized controlled trial DISCO on COPD screening interventions in primary care (3 intervention arms
column3: the investigators will carry out a pilot cross-sectional survey on the cessation process of smokers during the 2 years following their participation
column4: evaluating the incidence and modalities of cessation attempts of smokers belonging to an age group at risk of COPD (40-80 years) and who initially consulted their general practitioner for any reason 2 years ago at the time of their inclusion.

column1: The impact on future management could be the personalization of cessation advice given to smokers according to quantitative and qualitative indicators specific to their experience
column2: their previous history of smoking cessation
column3: their health situation and socio-demographic characteristics. Eventually
column4: a gradation of the levels of support offered to patients in general practice on the basis of predictive factors of smoking cessation could be studied.

column1: The investigators hypothesize that participation in COPD screening with the GP may be associated with patient progress in quitting smoking. This pilot study will be conducted on a random sample of 120 participants from the subgroup of 544 patients who were smokers at inclusion in DISCO.";2021-04-07T00:00:00;Actual;Completed;2021-07-07T00:00:00;Actual;2021-04-02T00:00:00;2021-04-05T00:00:00;Observational;Cross-Sectional;120.0;Actual;[];0.0;False;Undecided;Rennes University Hospital;['France'];['Romain NIFENECKER'
